The '''telecommunications industry''' within the sector of [[information and communication technology]] is made up of all [[Telecommunication]]s/[[Telephone company|telephone companies]] and [[internet service provider]]s and plays the crucial role in the evolution of [[mobile communication]]s and the [[information society]].
Traditional [[telephone call]]s continue to be the industry's biggest revenue generator, but thanks to advances in [[network technology]], Telecom today is less about [[voice call|voice]] and increasingly about text ([[messaging]], [[email]]) and images (e.g. [[video streaming]]). [[High-speed internet]] [[internet access|access]] for computer-based data applications such as [[Broadband service provider|broadband information service]]s and [[interactive entertainment]], is pervasive. [[Digital Subscriber Line]] (DSL) is the main broadband telecom technology. The fastest growth comes from ([[value-added service|value-added]]) [[network service|service]]s delivered over [[mobile network]]s.<ref name=investopedia/>
{{quote|The [[telecommunication|telecom]] sector continues to be at the epicenter for growth, innovation, and disruption for virtually any industry. [[Mobile device]]s and related [[broadband]] [[internet connectivity|connectivity]] continue to be more and more embedded in the fabric of society today and they are key in driving the momentum around some key trends such as [[video streaming]], [[Internet of Things]] (IoT), and [[mobile payment]]s.|Deloitte<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/pages/technology-media-and-telecommunications/articles/telecommunications-industry-outlook.html|title=2017 Telecommunications Industry Outlook - Deloitte US|website=Deloitte United States}}</ref>}}
{{quote|Think of telecommunications as the world's biggest machine. Strung together by complex [[telecommunications network|network]]s, [[telephone]]s, [[mobile phone]]s and [[internet]]-linked [[personal computer|PC]]s, the global system touches nearly all of us. It allows us to speak, share thoughts and do business with nearly anyone, regardless of where in the world they might be. Telecom operating companies make all this happen.|Investopedia<ref name=investopedia>{{cite web|url=http://www.investopedia.com/features/industryhandbook/telecom.asp|title=The Industry Handbook: The Telecommunications Industry|date=7 January 2004|publisher=}}</ref>}}
Insight Research<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insight-corp.com/reports/review15.asp|title=Insight Research - Telecom Market Research Reports, Industry Analysis, Custom Consulting Services|website=www.insight-corp.com}}</ref> projects that telecommunications services [[revenue]] worldwide will grow from $2.2 [[Trillion (short scale)|trillion]] in 2015 to $2.4 trillion in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/worldwide-telecommunications-industry-revenue-to-hit-24-trillion-in-2020-says-insight-research-300047963.html|title=Worldwide Telecommunications Industry Revenue to hit $2.4 Trillion in 2020, says Insight Research}}</ref>
==Market segmentation==
Of all the [[customer]] [[market (economics)|market]]s, residential and [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|small business]] markets are the toughest. With hundreds of players in the market, competitors rely heavily on price; success rests largely on brand name strength and investment in efficient [[Telecommunications billing|billing]] systems. The [[corporation|corporate]] market remains the industry's favorite. Big corporate customers are concerned mostly about the quality and reliability of their telephone calls and data delivery while being less price-sensitive than residential customers. [[Multinational corporation|Multinationals]], spend heavily on telecom infrastructure and premium services like [[Network security|high-security]] [[private network]]s and [[videoconferencing]]. Network connectivity can also be provided to other telecom companies by wholesaling circuits to heavy network users like internet service providers and large corporations. <ref name=investopedia/>
